      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="what-is-ide-jutge">
        <span>What is <b>ide.jutge</b>?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p><b>ide.jutge</b> is <i>Jutge.org</i>'s Web application to edit, compile, run and debug C++ programs.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="how-do-i-execute-my-programs">
        <span>How do I execute my programs?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>Choose the execution mode from the <a href="/documentation#exec-selector">Execution Selector</a>.</p>
          <img src="/img/doc/exec-menu.png" alt="Execution Selector">
          <p>There are essentially two execution categories:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><b>Non-debug:</b> <i>Run</i> and <i>Valgrind</i>.</li>
            <li><b>Debug:</b> <i>Debug</i> and <i>Slow motion</i>.</li>
          </ul>
          <p><i>Run</i> and <i>Valgrind</i> just execute the program, but the latter will
          report any memory-related errors found in the
          <a href="/documentation#valgrind-tab">Valgrind Tab</a>.</p>
          <p><i>Debug</i> and <i>Slow motion</i> let you take advantage of the IDE's debugging features.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="when-is-my-program-compiled">
        <span>When is my program compiled?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>Your program gets compiled every time you choose one of the execution modes 
          from the <a href="/documentation#exec-selector">Execution Selector</a>.</p>
          <p>Compilation errors will be reported in the 
          <a href="/documentation#diagnostics-tab">Diagnostics Tab</a>, and marked with the 
          <img src='data:image/png;base64,' alt="Error Icon">
          and 
          <img src='data:image/png;base64,' alt="Warning Icon">
          icons in the 
          <a href="/documentation#code-editor">Code Editor</a>'s gutter.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="why-is-debugging-so-awesome">
        <span>Why is debugging so awesome?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>Debugging lets you inspect what your code does in real-time! 
          By setting <i>breakpoints</i> (<img src="/img/jtg-breakpoint.png" alt="Breakpoint Icon">), 
          you can pause your program at any given point.
          </p>
          <p>
          While the program is paused you can:
          <ul>
            <li>See and modify the values of the variables in the <a href="/documentation#variables-tab">Variables Tab</a>.</li>
            <li>See the program's <i>call stack</i> in the <a href="/documentation#frames-tab">Frames Tab</a>.</li>
            <li>Evaluate C++ expressions in the <a href="/documentation#exprs-tab">Expressions Tab</a>.</li>
          </ul>
          </p>
          <p>
          You can also control the execution of the program using 
          the <a href="/documentation#debug-controls">Debug Controls</a>.
          When in <i>Debug</i> mode, the program will pause at the beginning on the <b>main</b> method.
          </p>
          <p>
          You can then resume execution with the <i>Continue</i> button 
          (<img src="/img/Continue.png" alt="Continue Button">) â€”the program will go on until it finishes 
          or another <i>breakpoint</i> is hit.
          </p>
          <p>
          Alternatively, you can execute the program line-by-line using the <i>Step</i> buttons 
          (<img src="/img/StepOver.png" alt="Step Over Button">, 
          <img src="/img/StepInto.png" alt="Step Into Button"> and 
          <img src="/img/StepOut.png" alt="Step Out Button">).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="how-do-i-add-remove-breakpoints">
        <span>How do I add/remove <i>breakpoints</i>?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>Click on the left side of the editor's gutter to add a breakpoint.
          The <img src="/img/jtg-breakpoint.png" alt="Breakpoint Icon"> icon indicates 
          the breakpoint has been set. Click again to remove the breakpoint.</p>
          <img src="/img/doc/breakpoint-add.png" alt="Add/Remove Breakpoint">
        </div>
      </div>
      
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="can-i-modify-variables-of-any-type">
        <span>Can I modify variables of any type?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p><b>Yes</b>, you can modify variables of any type, <b>but</b> there are some caveats:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Using the <a href="/documentation#variables-tab">Variables Tab</a>, 
            you can only modify <i>basic-type</i> variables. The complete list of supported types 
            can be found <a href="/documentation#modifiable-variable-types">here</a>.</li>
            <li>The <a href="/documentation#exprs-tab">Expressions Tab</a> may be used 
            to set variable values. However, special care must be taken in this case, 
            because <b>all expressions are reevaluated every time the program pauses</b>. 
            So, you will probably need to <b>remove the expression</b> right after evaluating it.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="so-how-do-i-add-remove-expressions">
        <span>So, how do I add/remove expressions?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>Click on the <i>Add</i> button to add an expression.</p>
          <p>Use the checkboxes to select the expressions you want to remove,
          and hit the <i>Remove</i> button.</p>
          <img src="/img/doc/expr-remove.png" alt="Remove Expression">
        </div>
      </div>
            
            
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="can-i-keep-my-ide-configuration-for-a-later-session">
        <span>Can I keep my IDE configuration for a later session?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>The following data is saved in your browser's <b>Local Storage</b>:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>C++ code in the editor.</li>
            <li><i>View</i> configuration (<i>Font size</i>, <i>IDE</i>
            and <i>Editor themes</i>).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>This means that you will keep everything if you browse to another page,
          close the IDE tab, or even close your browser!</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      
      <div class="jtg-doc-h2" id="my-program-is-taking-too-long">
        <span>My program is taking too long!</span>
      </div>
      <div class="jtg-doc-text">
        <div class="jtg-doc-par">
          <p>Are you sure it is not waiting for input (ie. <b>cin</b>, <b>scanf</b>)?</p>
          <p>If your program is taking longer than expected to finish, hit the <i>Pause</i> 
          button (<img src="/img/Pause.png" alt="Pause Button">) to see where execution is at.
          The current line will be highlighted in the code editor!</p>
          <p>If you find you program has gone into an infinite loop, just kill it with the 
          <i>Stop</i> button (<img src="/img/Kill.png" alt="Stop Button">).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      
